{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_bison_ver01/data/sn84024808/00295860704/1920101801/0180.xml":{"full_text":"GREAT FALLS DAILY TRIBUNE\nLEONARD a D1EHL\n'\u25a0If Bustneu Managt\ncl\nEditor\nManager\nEDITORIAL PAGE\nTHE DEPARTMENT OF AGRICULTURE\nThe record of achievements of the Department\nof Agriculture under Democratic rule stands in\nsharp contrast with the record of neglect of the\nAmerican farmers by the Republican congress,\naccording to Secretary of Agriculture, Edwin T.\nMeredith. In an interview recently, Mr. Mere\ndith cited many acts of the Democratic admin\nistration beneficial to the agricultural interests\nof the country, and arraigned the Republican\ncongress for its failure to appropriate funds to\ncarry on important work of the Department of\nAgriculture.\nSecretary Meredith asserted that many of the\nfeatures of the Agricultural Department advo\ncated by Senator Hording, the Republican candi\ndate for president, have been established by the\nDemocrats. He said these agencies for the bene\nfit of the American farmers would now be func\ntioning in full measure but for the indifference\nof the Republican congress. The Republican\nleaders, he said, have cheated the farmers of\nthese services by pretending to \"economize\" in\norder to secure votes.\n\"In no six years of the history of the country\nhas there been beneficient legislation in behalf\nof agriculture approaching in scope that which\nwas enacted during the period from 1912 to\n1918,\" said Mr. Meredith. During that period\nthe Democratic administration enacted the grain\nstandards act, the farm loan act, the Federal aid\nroad act, the Smith-Lever extension act estab\nlishing the county agent system, the cotton fu\ntures act, the United States warehouse act. and\nmany others, all having to do directly with the\nimprovement and development of agriculture,\nthe bettering of market conditions, and the fur\nnishing of facilities needed by the farmers to\nsecure credit for the prosecution of their opera\ntions.\n\"On the other hand, the Republican party\u2014\nthe Republicans having had absolute control of\nCongress during the last two years\u2014stands-con\nvicted* not only of not having passed any legisla\ntion of importance to agriculture, but of having\ncrippled work already begun or actively under\nway.\n\"Senator Harding talks to the farmers in\nglowing general terms of what should be done\nfor the agricultural interests of the country. But\nSenator Harding in advocating a study of mar\nkets, a study of costs, and a review of the\nworld situation regarding agriculture for the\nbenefit of the American farmers, is urging fea\ntures of the Department of Agriculture that are\nalready established and would be functioning in\nfull measure except for the indifference of a\nRepublican congress. The Republican leaders,\nin order to secure votes, played up 'economy'\nrather than to make reasonable and adequate\nappropriations for these services to the farmer.\n\"While the congress just adjourned appropri\nated, all told, approximately $5,500,000,000, only\none-fourth of one percent of this amount was pro\nvided for work relating directly to agriculture.\nAn industry capitalized at $80,000,000,000\u2014as\nmuch as is represented in all the railroads, all\nthe mines, all the manufacturing plants in the\nUnited States combined\u2014is entitled to some\nwhat more than one-fourth of one per cent of\nthe appropriations passed by congress. It is\nnot economy but the grossest mai-administration\non the part of a Republican congress to cut two\nmillion dollars from the agricultural appropria\ntion bill, making necessary a curtailment of\nmany important lines of work, simply to make\npolitical capital by showing that appropriations\nhave been reduced on the theory that the peo\nple will not see that it affects them adversely.\n\"Senator Harding urges the scientific study of\nthe world markets for farm products. This very\nthing is being done by the Bureau of Markets,\ncreated by a Democratic administration, so far\nas available funds permit. This bureau has a\nman stationed regularly in London to keep in\ntouch with the market situation abroad. It now\nhas two men in South America who are endeav\noring to aid in stimulating the trade with this\ncountry in pure bred live stock. It has sent ex\nperts to Australia and the Far East to investi\ngate the markets for American products, and\nmembers of its grain divisjpn, about a year ago,\nsecured first hand information regarding the\ngrain, and especially the wheat, situation abroad.\nThe data resulting from these studies are made\navailable through publications and otherwise.\nFurthermore, the Bureau of Crop Estimates re\nceives reports regularly regarding crop condi\ntions abroad, and these also are made public\nthrough appropriate channels.\n\"There is an International Institute of Agri\nculture at Rome, to which the agricultural coun\ntries of the world send a resident delegate and,\nfrom time to time, special delegates for confer\nence The permanent delegate is recommended\ntn the State Department by the Secretary of Ag\nriculture A search has been made for a man\nqualified to represent the United States but it\nS m been impossible to find anyo^: who could,\nor would, accept the appointment on the basis\nof the present compensation. The place carries\nan appropriation of $3,600, from which must be\npaid the cost of the round trip to Europe, living\nexpenses for one year, and salary. I earnestly\nurged that this be increased to $7,500, so that\na man with requisite scientific training and a\nthorough knowledge of agriculture\u2014a man cap\nable of looking after the interests of the United\nStates\u2014might be secured. This recommenda\ntion was made to the last Republican congress,\nbut Congress refused to take the action suggest\ned and consequently the United States is now\nwithout proper representation at the Institute.\"''\nA FOUR FLUSHING CAMPAIGN\nWe note that credit is being claimed for Carl\nRiddick on account of the seed money disbursed\nby the Federal government in 1918 to the dry\nland farmers of this section who had neither\ncash nor credit to purchase seed after a total\ncrop failure. This money came out of the hun\ndred million dollar fund voted by congress to\nthe president to be spent at his discretion for\nwar purposes where no appropriation existed\nto cover the expense. Congressman Carl Riddick\nhad nothing to do with it. A dispatch under\ndate of October 13 from Senator Walsh fully\nevplains the matter. The dispatch follows:\nChicago, Oct. 13, 1920.\n\"Hon. J. T. Carroll, Helena, Mont.\n\"Riddick claim absurd. I secured seed loan\nfund. Inducing president to set aside five mil\nlion of his hundred million war fund for that\npurpose through appeals to President Wilson\nand Secretaries Houston and McAdoo. This was\nin fall of 1918 before Riddick went to Washing\nton. No money for seed was secured after he\ncame. No loans were cancelled. Obligations\nstill exist. Lien was released in cases where\ncrop fell below five bushels to the acre. Action\ntaken on resolution of Judge Lobdell farm loan\nboard after personal investigation.\n\"Fort Peck extension bill was senate not house\nbill. Shall write more fully.\n\"T. J. WALSH.\"\nSo far as we recollect neither of our senators\never claimed any special credit for getting this\nmoney to relieve the urgent needs of the\ndrouth stricken farmers of Montana, Dakota\nand Wyoming. Doubtless the senators and\nrepresentatives of all the states affected were\nvery glad to aid Senator Walsh in making such\nrepresentations as were effective to the presi\ndent at the time. If any one man is entitled to\nclaim any credit in the matter it is the president,\nWoodrow Wilson, who had sole and absolute\ncontrol over the fund from which the money\ncame. The president was convinced that he\nwas doing his duty and carrying out the will of\ncongress when he diverted five per cent of this\ntrust fund for the purchase of seed wheat for\ndrouth stricken farmers in the northwest. We\nnever heard that he claimed any credit for doing\nhis duty as he saw it\nRiddick and his friends to try and make the\nfarmers of this state believe that he did it, and\nwas the only friend they had in time of need at\nWashington. It is characteristic of the man\nand his political methods.\nIt remained for Carl\nPROGRESSIVE TTEADER.\nProgressive in legislation, firm in war and in\ndustrial crises, Governor Cox has made good to\nthe people of Ohio as he stands ready to make\ngood to the people of the United States.\nSAFETY VALVE.\n\"Public opinion is the most interesting char\nacteristic of a democracy,\" says Governor Cox.\nIt is the real safety valve to the institutions\nof a free government.\"\nHELPS SCHOOLS.\nState aid for weak school districts was made\npossible in Ohio through the efforts of Governor\nCox. He favors increasing \u00eeeachers' salaries.\nHAS MADE GOOD.\nGovernor Cox has made good in Ohio. Forty\ntwo basic reforms were written into the state\nconstitution under his leadership.\nOpinions: of\nSO RUNS THE WORLD AWAY.\n(Ohio State Journal.)\nSic transit gloria mundi, as we say in Ohio, and it's only\na few weeks since Governor Sproul was a household word,\nand now all thr,t ever happens to him is to be put on an oc\ncasional advisory committee.\nCHANCE TO VIEW WITH ALARM.\n(Chicago News.)\nWhile the foes of alcohol are meeting in Washington they\ncan find several things to do besides gloat, if they will look\nover the police reports from almost anywhere.\nLOT OF OTHERS IN SAME BOAT.\n(Indianapolis News.)\nGerard says that be would be thankful if he could\n$1,000,000. So would almost any of us.\nget\nIT.\nFOOLS STILL FALL FOR\nv (Baltimore Sun.)\nCommunism is merely the age-old dream of suckers that\nsomething may be got for nothing.\nTHE HASKIN LETTER\nBy FREDERIC',\nh A SKIN\nPRESIDENTIAL CAMPAIGNS.\nXIX\u2014The McKinley Bryan Race of 1896.\nWashington, D. G., Oct. 6.\u2014The hard\nest fought political battle of American\nhistory was the campaign of 1896 in\nwhich William McKinley of Ohio, van\nquished William Jennings Bryan of Ne\nbraska. The fact that McKinley was\nre-elected with ease in his second cam\npaign against Bryan, and that the Re\npublican majorities of 1896 look so great\nOn paper, has caused many men of short\nmemory to believe that McKinley won\nhis first election without great difficulty.\nat -u' 18 year the Democratic nominee,\nMr. Bryan made the most remarkable\nspeaking campaign ever undertaken by\nany man. In thfl'same year, the Repub\nlican campaign manager, Mr. Hanna,\nspent five times as much money as had\never been spent before in a presidential\nrace. The Republican campaign as con\nducted with such consumate skill that the\nname of Mark Hanna will live for years\nL\u00e0s that of the best political general the\n1 country has oroduced.\nThe year 1896 was a year of political\nrevolution. Both of the leading parties\nunderwent great changes, and the num\nber of Independent voters was increased\na thousand fold. Mr. Cleveland's second\nadministration began with the country on\nthe verge of a financial crash. The blow\ndescended and the panic of 1893 was on.\nThe money question, which both parties\nhad so carefully side-stepped for so many\nyears was presented in such a way that\nthe administration could not avoid \"taking\na position. Mr. Cleveland and his cabi\nnet decided to place the country squarelv\non the gold standard, and to disregard the\npetty sops which had been thrown to\nsilver. The treasury regulations accom\npjished this purpose long before the Mc\nKinley administration came in.\nDemocrats in Control.\nFor the first time since the first part\nof Buchanan's administration the govern\nment was in the control of the Demo\ncrats, that party having the president\nand a majority in both houses of con\ngress. Mr. Cleveland called congress to\ngether and urged the repeal of the silver\npurchasing clause of the Sherman net,\nwhich would finally \"demo<netize'' silver.\nHis party did not agree with him on that\nsubject, and it wa^with the greatest dif\nficulty that his purpose was accomplish\ned\nPresident Cleveland had been an ex\namplar of civil service reform and was\nopposed to \"pernicious activity\" in po\nlitics, but he went to the extreme of the\nuse of patronage as a club to drive the\nrepeal bill through congress. Even then,\nit wa\u00bb done .inly by the help of east\nern Republican votes. It left his party\nhopelessly divided.\nThe Democratic landslide which re\nelected Cleveland was the result of pop\nular disapproval of the McKinley tariff\nbill of 1890. After the terrific fight ou\nthe silver purchasing clause repeal, the\nDemocratic congress endeavored to enact\na Democratic tariff bill. The party was\nalready torn asunder and could act with\nno unanimitv. The result was the pas\nsage of the Wilson bill, which Mr. Cleve\nland permitted to become a law without\nhis signature.\nAs the people had condemned the Mc\nKinley bill six months after it was passed\nand before its effect could possiblv have\nbeen felt, by the election of the Demo\ncratic house in 1890, so the Wilson bill,\ncharged with responsibility for a uanii\nwhich was on before the bill was written,\nresulted in the overwhelming Republican\ncongresional victory of 1S94.\nA Year of Split Parties.\nAll through the three years of the\nCleveland administration leading up to\nthe campaign of 1896 there waa constant\nstrife iu both parties. For a time it\nseemed that the Republicans would de\nclare for free silver and that the Demo\ncrats would follow their president in\nadvocacy for the gold standard. Then\nit seemed that both parties would de\nclare for the gold standard and the silver\nhosts would enroll under the banner of\nPopulism. The Republicans felt certain\nthat, they could win on the prosperity\nissue, and by denouncing the Cleveland\nadministration for its issue of $262.000,\nOOO of bonds in \"time of profound peace.\"\nI But they didn't want to split their own\nforces by taking sides in the money fight,\nj Mr. McKinley amd Speaker Thomas B.\nReed were the leading candidates for the\nRepublican nomination for president.\nMr. McKinley lind the good fourtune to\nhave Murk Ilanna for his political cap\ni tain. Hanna organized the states and\ntook even New England away from Reed\nlong before the convention met. Mr.\nHanna wns afraid of the money question\nand Mr. McKinley was committed by his\nrecord to \"bimetallism.\" So the Ohio\nleaders attempted to \"straddle\" the issue\nonce more. The Ohio state platform\ncontained a delphic utterance on the\nmoney question which said nothing.\nBut when 'he national convention met\nat St. Louis. Mr. Hanna found that the\nquestion was one which was too big to\nbe straddled. Senator Thomas C. Piatt\nof Now York, forced Hanna to accept\na gold standard platform. It was later\nmodified by a pronouncement in favor i\nof international bimetallism, which per- j\nBurglars Loot Home\nof Much Furnishings\nWhile Family Absent\nSpecial to the Daily Tribune.\nButte. Oct. 17.--When burglars en\ntered the home of Mr. and Mrs. Charles\nE. Soper in this city they not only took\nsome of the smaller articles about the\nhouse. The ru gof the living room, a\nrug valued at $250. was taken, as were\nalso four diner chairs, table and bed\nlinen, also the clothing of Mr. and Mrs.\nSoper and four Navajo blankets. An\nattempt was made to remove the j-ug of\nthe dining room, but a heavy heating\nstove seems to have prevented that at\ntempt. The robbery happened when\nthe family was temporarily absent in\nthe down town part of the city.\nMeeting in November\nDecide on College\nSpecial to the Daily Tribune.\nBillings, Oct. 17.\u2014Church people\nmeeting at. Helena November 10 will\ndiscuss the proposal to make the Bil\nlings Polytechnic institute the state in\nterdenominational school, it, was learned\nyesterday at the adjournment of the\nCongregational conference of Montana\nIt is lanned to form a board of trus\ntees for the school, with a number of\ndenominations represented.\nAnaconda Officials\nArrive From Elast\nSpecial to the Daily Tribune.\nButte, Oct. 17.\u2014John D. Ryan, chair\nman of the board of directors, and C. J.\nKelley, president of the Anaconda Cop\nper Mining company, have arrived in\nButte in their special car from New\n,York City. While here they will in\nspect the properties in Butte of the\ncompany, and will settle upon working\nplans for the coming season.\nTapirs have three toes on their hind\ntfeet and four on their front feet.\npitted Republicans who had been shout\ning for silver to come down gracefully.\nSenator Piatt may not be regarded as a\ngreat statesman, but in 1896 and 1900\nhe did things that left marks on the\nhistory of the country.\nWesterners Bolted.\nWhen the gold plank was adopted, 84\nwestern Republican delegates, headed by\nSenator Teller of Colorado, Senator Can\nnon of Utah, and Senator Dubois of\nIdaho, walked out of the convention and\ninto the Democratic party. All over the\ncountry there were Republicans who\nloudly proclaimed the fact that they nad\nbolted the nomination of McKinley. A\nnational silver Republican convention\nwas called. Mr. Hanna, chosen chair\nman of the national committee, knew that\nhe had a great job ahead of him and he\nset to work.\nThe Democratic convention met in\nChicago. The Cleveland wing of the\nparty controlled the national committee,\nbut the recommendations of that body\nwere swept aside on the first vote and\nit was clear that the silver men con\ntrolled th\u00e7 convention. A resolution com\nmending the then present Democratic\nconvention was voted down with venge\nful hoots. No man was ever hated more\nthan the Democratic national conversion\nof 1896 hated Grover Cleveland, the\nDemocratic president of the United\nStates.\nLeading free silver advocates like\nRichard P. Bland of Missouri, and John\nR\u00bb McLean of Ohio, were contesting for\nthe nomination. The story of their de\nfeat is a most familiar bit of political\nhistory. William Jennings Bryan, who\nhod reported the St. Louis convention\nwhich nominated McKinley, for a Ne\nbraska newspaper, came to Chicago fit\nthe head of a contesting delegation, lie\nwas given a seat. Then came the great\ndebate on the platform. The eastern\nDemocrats fighting hard against the\nmajority. Tn that debate, Sir. Bryan,\nthen only 36 years old, slim of figure and\nfull of mane, leaped into world-wide fame\nin a moment. The famous \"crown of\nthorns and cross of gold\" speech,\nwhether the figure was borrowed from\nRepresentative MeCall of Massachusetts\nor (not, sent that convention wild. Bryan\nwas nominated.\nTriumph of the Boy Orator.\nA little later the Populists and the\nSilver Republicans also nominated \"the\nBoy Orator of the Platte.\" The Cleve\nland Democrats_ called a convention at\nIndianapolis aniForganb-ed the \"National\nDemocracy.\" General John M. Palmer\n\u2022>f Illinois, a soldier of the Union, was\nnominated for president, with General\nSimon Bolivar Buckner of Kentucky, a\nsoldier of the confederacy, for vice presi\ndent. They polled but few votes, the\nmajority of the gold Democrats voting\nstraight for McKinley.\nBryan soon began his unprecedented\nand unequalled campaign tour. He did\nnot then possess the suavity of his\nlater years, but he was mightily in\nearnest. No other man bas ever aroused\ntfife enthusiasm which he created in that\ncampaign. He spoke to over 5.000.000\npeople, making over a thousand separate\nspeeches. In the first part of jthe cam\npaign he traveled in ordinary day\ncoaches, the /ailroads making it as hard\nfor him as possible. Toward the end of\nthe campaign the railroads relented and\ntie was enabled to get a private car. He\nwas without money and in his great can\nvass was sometimes forced to borrow\nthe price of a 'icket to the next storing\nplace.\nAgainst ih 'is terrific campaign, which\nseemed to be sweeping the country for\nthe Democrats, Mr. Hanna planned the\ngreat \"campaign of education.\" The\nfarmers of the agricultural states cast\nof the Mississippi were induced to be\nlieve that the election of Bryan would\nmean bankruptcy for them. All of the\nwealth of the country was back of Hanna\n\u2014he had millions to spend and he knew\nhow to do it.\nCareful canvasses taken two months\nbefore the election showed that such\nstates as Ohio and Indiana were for\nBryan. The *\"ork that was done to turn\nthat defeat into the overwhelming victory\nin November was due to the political\nsagacity of Marcus A. Hanna.\nBryan's appeals to the people of every\nsection, the enormous popular interest in\nhis personality and the picturesqueness\nof his campaign, on the one side, and the\nefforts of the Republicans to reach every\nvoter with campaign literature and per\nsonal argument on the other side, result\ned in a widespread popular interest in\npolitics as had never been known.\nWhile the campaign was decisive, and\nwhile it. practically settled the money\nquestion for all time, defeat did not. di\nminish the popularity of the Democratic\nstandard-bearer, who has ever since\nstood high iu the councils of his party.\nMcKinley was chosen president and his\nadministration witnessed the return of\nprosperity, the greatest the country has\nknown. Atter all. not the least\namong the Republican assets of 1S96 was\nthe fact that the panic of 1893 came dur\ning a Democratic administration.\nAutomobile Thief\nRuns Car Off Cliff\nInto Yellowstone\n__ __\nday search was conducted, and af night\nfall the theory, was held that the thief\nhad simply sent the big car over the\nprecipice after he had made use of it.\nThe car was stolen October 8, from\nW. C. Carlson. The only clues to the\nthief are a small note book, its pages\nblank, and a gloove. The car was one\nof a number of large automobiles miss\ning lately. Whisky runners are be\nlieved to have taken them.\nSpecial to the Daily Tribune.\nBillings, Oct. 17.\u2014The finding of the\nruins of a stolen automobile at the foot\nof a 150 foot cliff on the Yellowstone\nriver near here yesterday morning caus\ned the police to believe that bodies\nwould be found in the str\u00e7arn. An all\nChanges in the N. P.\nOperating Officers\nSpecial to the Dally Tribune.\nLivingston, Oct. 17.\u2014Change\u00ab in the\nsuperintendency of Northern Pacific di\nvisions, effective Oct. I\u00df, have been an\nnounced by the general headquarters of\nthe road here.\nCol. T. H. Lantry, who has been su\nperintendent of the Montana division\nwith headquarters at Livingston for the\npast seven months, has been pro\nmoted to become superintendent of the\nSeattle division of the road with head\nquarters at Seattle.\nSucceeding Superintendent Lantry on\nthe Montana division G. II. Jacobus, su\nperintendent of the Yellowstone division,\ncomes to Livingston. Mr. Jacobus was\nformerly assistant to the general super\nintendent here. He will be succeeded\nat Giendive by W. C. Sloan, who goes\nfrom the office of the superintendent of\nthe Pasco division to the superintendency\nof the Yellowstope division.\nNo country in the world approaches\nthe United States for the quality of\napples produced.\nBy the Governor of the State of Montan\u00bb\nA PROCLAMATION.\nBy virtue of the authority in me vest\ned by the Constitution and the Laws oi\nthe State of Montana, I, S. V. Stewart,\nGovernor of said State, do hereby pro\nclaim that on Tuesday, the second day\nof November, A. D. 1920 there will be\nheld in the State of Montana a general\nelection by the qualified electors of said\nState, to elect the following officers, to\nwit:\nFour Presidential electors; one Repre\nsentative in Congress for the First Con\ngressional District; one Repre\nsentative in Congress for the Second Con\ngressional District; one Governor; one\nLieutenant Governor; two Associate Jus\ntices of the Supreme Court each for a\nsix year term; one Associate Justice of\nthe Supreme Court for tbe unexpired\nterm ending the first Monday In Janu\nary, 1923; one Secretary of State; one\nAttorney General; one State Treasurer;\none State Auditor; one Superintendent\nof Public Instruction; one Railroad Com\nmissioner;\nMembers of the House of Representa\ntives for the several counties of the State\n'as follows, to-wit:\nBeaverhead, 1; Big Horn, 1; Blaine, 1;\nBroadwater, 1; Carbon, 3; Carter, 1;\nCascade, 6; Chouteau, 4; Custer, \u00ce; Dan\niels, 1; Dawson 3; Deer Lodge 3; Fallon\n1; Fergus 4; Flathead 4; Gallatin 8; Gar\nfield 1; Glacier 1; Golden Valley 1; Gran\nite 1; HUI 1; Jefferson 1; Lewis and\nClark 5; Liberty 1; Lincoln 1; McCone 1;\nMadison 2; Meagher 1; Mineral 1; Mis\nsoula 5; Musselshell 1; Park 2; Phillips 1;\nPondera 1; Powell 1; Powder River 1;\nPrairie, 1; Ravalli, 2; Richland, 1; Roose\nvelt, 1; Rosebud, 2; Sanders, 1; Sheridan,\n1; Silver Bow, 12; Stillwater, 1; Sweet\nGrass, 1; Teton, 2; Toole, 1; Treasure, 1;\nValley, S; AVibaux, 1; Wheatland, 1;\nYellowstone, 6.\nJudges of the District Court in the\nvarious Judicial districts as follows, to\nwlt:\nFirst District, 2; Second District 3;\nThird District 1; Fourth District 3; Fifth\nDistrict 2; Sixth District 1; Seventh Dis\ntrict 1; Eighth District 2; Ninth District\n1; Tenth District 2; Eleventh District 1;\nTwelfth District 1; Thirteenth District 2;\nFourteenth District 1; Fifteenth District\n1; Sixteenth District 2*; Seventeenth Dis\ntrict 1; Eighteenth District 1; Nineteenth\nDistrict 1; Twentieth District 1.\nThere will also be submitted to the\nqualified electors of the State at said\ngeneral election a proposed amendment\nto Section 15 of Article XII of the Con\nstitution of the State of Montana, as\nprescribed by Chapter 47 of the Laws or\nthe Sixteenth Legislative Assembly, be\ning an act entttled:\n\"An Act for the submission to the qual\nified electors of the State of Montana of\nan amendment to Section 15 of Article\nXII of the Constitution as amended;\ncreating County Board of Equalization,\nand a State Tax Commission, and defin\ning their powers and duties.\"\nThere will also be submitted to the\nqualified electors of the State at said\ngeneral election a proposed amendment\nto Section 5 of Article XI of the Consti\ntution of the State of Montana, as pre\nscribed by Chapter 149 of the Laws of\nthe Sixteenth Legislative Assembly, be\ning an act entitled:\n\"An Act to submit to the qualified\nelectors of the State of Montana an\namendment to Section 5 of Article II of\nthe Constitution of the State of Montana,\nproviding that 95 per centum of all the\ninterest received on the school funds of\nthe State and 95 per centum of all the\nother income from the school funds of\nthe State shall be apportioned to the sev\neral school districts of the State; and\nfurther providing that the remaining five\nper centum of all the interest received\non the School Funds of the State and\nthe remaining five .per centum of all the\nother Income from the school funds of\nthe State shall be added to the public\nschool funds of the State and become a\npermanent part thereof.\"\nThere will also be submitted to the\nqualified electors of the State at said\ngeneral election a proposed amendment\nto Section 20 of Article VII of the Con\nstitution of the State of Montana, as\nprescribed by Chapter 25 of the Laws of\nthe Extraordinary Session of the Six\nteenth Legislative Assembly, being an\nact entitled\n\"An Act for the submission to the qual\nified electors of the State of Montana of\nan amendment to Section 20 of Article 7\nof the Constitution of the State of Mon\ntana creating a board of Examiners and\ndefining and prescribing its powers and\nduties; authorising the Legislative Assem\nbly to create a Board of Administration\nand defining and prescribing its powers\nand duties and authorizing the Legislative\nAssembly to create such administrative\ndepartments as the interests of the State\nmay require, and in creating such de\npartments the Legislative Assembly may\nconsolidate or abolish any boards, offices\nand bureaus created by Statutory Law,\nand define and prescribe their functions,\npowers and duties.\"\nThere will also be submitted to the\nqualified electors of the State at said\ngeneral elecrtion Referendum Measure Is o.\n13, which Is a reference to the people by\nreferendum petition of Senate Bill No.\n142, being Chapter 113 of the Laws of the\nSixteenth Legislative Assembly, and be\ning an act entitled:\n\"An Act to provide for the nomination\nof candidates of the different political\nparties by direct vote and provide for\nthe election of delegates and alternate\ndelegates to State Conventions and pro\nviding for the holding of the State Con\nvention and for the nomination of can\ndidates thereat, and for the election of\nCounty and State Committeemen of po\nlitical parties, and to provide for the\nmanner of the organization of new po\nlitical parties, and to provide for inde\npendent nomination, and to repeal Initia\nted BUI entitled: 'A Bill to propose by\nInitiative Petition a law to provide for\nparty nominations by direct vote,' ap\nproved and passed by the people of Mon\ntana at the general election of 1912; and\nto repeal Initiated Bill entitled: 'A Bill\nto propose by Initiative Petition a law to\nprovide for the expression by the people\nof the State of Montana of their prefer\nence of party candidates for President\nand Vice President of the United States\nat Presidential Conventions, and the nom\nination of Presidential electors by direct\nvote.' passed by the peoole-of Montana\nat the general election of 1912, and pro\nviding for a referendum of said Act at\na special election and providing for a\nspecial election to be held on the first\nTuesday in September, 3919, and provid\ning that said special election shail be\nheld under the provisions of the law of j\nthe State of Montana, and providing the\ntime when said act shall take effect.\"\nThere will also be submitted to the\nqualified electors of the State of Mon\ntana at said general election Referendum\nMeasure No, 14, which is a reference to\nthe neopie bv the Legislative Assembly\nof Substitute for House Bill No. S3, be\ning Chanter 190 of the Laws of the Six\nteenth Legislative Assembly, and being\nan act entlttled\n\"An Act establishing Athletic Com\nmissions. and regulating boxing, spar\nring and wrestling in the State of Mon\ntana, and providing that 50 per cent of\nthe net receipts realized from such ex\nhibitions shall be paid into the State\nTreasury and be held and used for the\nsupport and maintenance of a home for\nreturned and disabled soldiers, sailors\nand marines of the World War and pro\nviding for a referendum of said act at\na special election to be held on the first\nTuesdav in September, 1919. under the\nprovisions of tRe Laws of the State of\nMontana.\"\nThere will also be submitted to the\nqualified electors at the said general\nelection Referendum Measure No. 15,\nwhich is a reference to the peoplo by ref\nerendum petition of Senate Bill No. 32,\nbeing Chapter 28 of the Laws of the Ex\ntraordinary Session of the Sixteenth Leg\nislative Assembly, and being an act en\ntitled:\n\"An Act to amend Sections 2, 3, 10. 16.\n21 and 32, and to repeal Sections 20 and\n22 of the law initiated and passed by the\npeople of the State of Montana at the\ngeneral election of 1912, entitled. 'A Bill\nto propose by Initiative petition a law\nto provide for party nominations by dl\nreot vote,' and to add these new sections\nthereto to be known as Section SA, SB.\n3C; and declaring this act to be an emer\ngency law and a law necessary for the\nImmediate preservation of the publlo\nhealth, peace and safety.\"\nThere will also be submitted to the\nqualified elector\u00ab of the State at said\ngeneral election Referendum Measure No.\n16. wlilch is a reference to the people by\nreferendum petition of Senate Bill No,\n80, being Chapter 27 of the Laws of the\nExtraordinary Session of the Sixteenth\nLegislative Assembly and being an act\nentitled:\n\"An Act to repeal Initiative measure\nentttled: 'A Bill to propose by initiative\npetition a law to provide for the sxpres\nsion by the people of the State of Mon- 1\ntana of their preference of party candi\ndates for President and Vice President of\nthe United States, the election of dele\ngates to Presidential conventions, and\nthe nomination of Presidential electors\nby direct vote,' initiated and passed by\nthe people of Montana at the general\nelection of 1912, and declare this act to\nbe an emergency law necessary for the\nimmediate preservation of the publlo\npeace and safety.\"\nT here will also be sumbitted to the\nqualified electors of the State at said\nne \u00ceX* election Referendum Measure\nNo. 23, which is a reference to the peo\np l e Legislative Assembly of Sen\nate Bill No. 46, being Chapter 169 of the\nLaws of the Sixteenth Legislative As\nsembly submitting to the qualified elect\norsI of the State of Montana the prop\nosition whether State bonds shall be 1s\nf\u00b0r Fifteen Million Dollars ($15,\n000,000) for State Highways, and which\nsaid act is entitled:\n\"An Act authorizing the State of Mon\ntana to become Indebted in the sum of\nFifteen Million Dollars ($15,000,000) in\nexcess of the Constitutional limit over\nand above any bonded indebtedness\nheretofore Incurred or created and for\nState is now obligated; pro\nviding for the issuance and sale of bonds\nor and in the name of the State of Mon\ntana in the sum of Fifteen Million Dol\nlars ($16,000,000) to acquire funds for the\nconstruction and building of public high\nly 8 V?. known and designated as\nState Highways; prescribing the form\nor such bonds; providing for the creation\nof a fund to pay the principal and inter\nest of said bonds by levying a sufficient\nannual tax to pay the principal and In\nterest accruing thereon; and such por\ntion of the money derived from license\nfees on motor vehicles, as the Legisla\nture may set aside for that purpose from\ntime to time. Providing for the submis\nsion to the qualified electors of the\nState of Montana at the next general\nelection the question of the issuance of\nsuch bonds and describing the form of\n\u00a3.1\u2014 ^e used and the duties of the\nState Board of Examiners relative to the\nIssuance of such bonds and the duties of\nthe .-secretary of State of Montana rel\natlve to the submission of said Question\nto tha qua Iff led electors.\"\nwill also be submitted to the\nqualified electors of the State at said\ngeneral election Initiative Measure No.\nIS, being entitled:\n\"A Bill to enaot by the Initiative a law\nto increase the rate of taxation on real\nana personal property for state pur\nposes one and one-half (1%) mills on\neach dollar of valuation for a period of\nten years, beginning with the year 1921,\nand to authorize and empower the Leg\nislative Assembly to levy a tax for each\nyear during such period of not exceeding\nthree and one-half (34) mills on each\ndollar of valuation, and to appropriate\nthe moneys derived from the one and\none-half (1%) mills of such levy for each\nyear during such period for the support,\nmaintenance and Improvement of the in\nstitutions now comprised in the Univer\nsity of Montana.\"\nThere will also be submitted to the\nqualified electors of the State at said\ngeneral election Initiative Measure No.\n19, submitting to the qualified electors\nof the State of Montana the proposition\nwhether State Bonds shall be issued for\nFive Million Dollars ($5,000,000) for edu\ncational purposes, and which said act is\nentitled:\n\"A Bill to enact by the Initiative a\nlaw to authorise the State of Montana\nto become Indebted in the sum of Five\nMillion Dollars ($5,000,000) in excess of\nthe Constitutional limitation of indebt\nedness and over and above any bonded\nindebtedness heretofore incurred or cre\nated and for which the State of Montana\nIs now obligated, for the construction,\nrepair and equipment of necessary build\nings at the several educational institu\ntions of the State of Montana now under\nthe control of the State Board of Educa\ntion, and consisting of the State Univer\nsity at Missoula, the State College of\nAgriculture and Mechanical Arts at Boze\nman, the Montana State School of Mines\nat Butte, and the Montana State Normal\nCollege a Dillon comprised in the Uni\nversity of Montana, and the State Or\nphan's Home at Twin Bridges, the Mon\ntana School for the Deaf and Blind at\nBoulder, the Montana State Industrial\n8chool at Mile\u00ab City and the State Vo\ncational School for Girls at Helena: pro\nviding for the issuance of bonds in the\nname of the State of Montana as evi\ndenoe of such -indebtedness and for the\nsale thereof; prescribing the form of\nsuch bonds; and providing for the levy\ning of an annual tax sufficient to pay\nthe principal thereof and the interest ac\ncruing thereon.\"\nThere will also be submitted to the\nqualified, electors of the State of Mon\ntana at said general election Initiative\nMeasure No. 20. submitting to the qual\nified electors of the State of Montana the\nproposition whether State Bonds shall be\nissued for Twenty Million Dollars ($20.\n000,000) for irrigation and reclamation\npurposes, and which said act is entitled:\n\"A Bill to propose by Initiative petition\na law providing that the State of Mon\ntana shall have control over the financ\ning of Irrigation Districts, and the con\nstruction and acquisition of irrigation\nsystems within such districts; authoriz\ning the State of Montana to become in\ndebted In the sum of Twenty Million\nDollars ($20,000,000) over and above any\nexisting indebtedness; providing for the\nIssuance and sale of such bonds in the\nname of the State of Montana in the\nsum of Twenty Million Dollars ($20.\n000.000) as state obligations; to acquire\nfunds for t\u00a3e purpose of creating a State\nfund to be' known as the \"Montana Ir\nrigation Development Fund,\" with which\nto purchase bonds of Irrigation Districts\norganized under the laws of Montana:\nprescribing the authority and duty of\nthe State Board of Examiners relative\nto the isst\u00efance of such bonds and the\nsale of Irrigation District bonds and the\ninvestment of the proceeds derived there\nfrom, as well as other money in the\n'Montana Irrigation Development Fund:\"\nprescribing the duties of State Boards\nand Officers in the administration of\nthis act, and providing for the submis\nsion of this act to the qualified electors.\"\nAt said general election there will be\nelected the following officers in each\ncounty, to-wlt:\nOne County Commissioner for a six\nyear term: one Sheriff; one County\nClerk; one County Treasurer; one Assess\nor; one County Attorney; one Clerk of\nthe District Court; one County Super\nintendent of Common Schools; one Cor\noner; one Public Administrator; one\nCounty Surveyor; one Countv Auditor in\neach county of the State entitled to such\nofficer.\nOfficers will also be elected at said\ngeneral election to fill any vacancy ex\nisting in any State or County office\nwhere such vacancy exists otherwise\nthan bv expiration of term of office.\nAlso to determine any local question to\nbe submitted to the electors of any\nCounty.\nAnd in order that such election may\nbo conducted in a quiet and orderly\nmanner, I hereby offer a reward of One\nHundred Dollars ($100.00) for the arrest\nand conviction of any person vlolattng\nany of the provisions of Title IV, Part\n1, of the Penal Code, such rewards to be\npaid until the total amount hereafter\nexpended for such purposes reaches the\nsum of Five Thousand Dollars.\nIN WITNESS WHEREOF I have here\nunto set my hand and caused the Great\nSeal of the State of Montana to be af\nfl IX)NT3 at the City of Helena, the Cap\nital, this the Seventh Day of August, in\nthe vear of our Lord one thousand nine\nhundred twenty and of the Independence\nof the United States of America the one\nhundred forty-fifth.\n(SEAL) S. V. STEWART.\nBy the Governor.\nC. T. STEWART.\nSecretary of State.\nAmerican Bank Trust\nCo. of Great Falls\nOFFICERS:\nr. Reckarde .-...President\nK. Flowerree\u201e. Vice-President\nH. O. Leaoher.... Vice-President\nF. O. Nelson Cashier\nP. X. Fisher Assistant Cashier\n\u2022nmwrTnnii.\nDIRECTORS:\nW. W. Hatght\nFrank W. Mitchell\n\u00ce. J. Flaherty\nU E. Foster\nRobert Cameron\nf. O. Nelson\nR. p. Reckarda\nH. G. Leaoher\nC. S. Heise?\nAlbert J. F ou\u00abk\nC. B. Roberta\nAlfred Malroboi-s\nClyde Wilooa\nCharles Horning\nW. K. Flowerre*\nWalter Kennedy\n___ JUVSUMVt \u00bbw\u00bb \u00abVVUUDU J\nChas. Glea Wa. Grills Fred A. Woehner\nCharles R. Taylor K. L. Norrie\n4% Interest on Time Certificates aarf\nSavings Accounts.","height":"22872","width":"17568"}}
